# Not All Data Deserves the Same Lock on the Door

Here's a mistake a lot of organizations make: they treat all their data the same way. Encrypt everything, restrict everything, lock everything down — which sounds secure until you realize it makes people route around the system because it's too slow to actually work with. Or worse, the opposite happens: nothing gets classified, and a spreadsheet full of patient data ends up sitting in the same unprotected folder as the company holiday party flyer.

The fix isn't more security everywhere — it's *proportional* security, based on what the data actually is.

The scenario: a healthcare provider handling patient medical records (PHI), employee data (PII), financial data, research data, business operations data, and public marketing content — all under HIPAA, GDPR, and state privacy law.

## Four Levels, Not One Blanket Rule

| Level | Description | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| **PUBLIC** | Approved for release; no harm if disclosed | Marketing materials, public website content |
| **INTERNAL** | Internal use only; low risk if disclosed but not intended for the public | Internal memos, organizational charts, meeting notes |
| **CONFIDENTIAL** | Disclosure could cause harm to individuals or the organization | Employee PII, financial data, vendor contracts |
| **RESTRICTED** | Disclosure could cause severe harm; highest sensitivity | Protected Health Information (PHI), authentication credentials, encryption keys |

## What Changes at Each Level

| Requirement | Public | Internal | Confidential | Restricted |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Labeling** | No | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| **Encryption at Rest** | No | No | Yes | Yes (AES-256 or equivalent) |
| **Encryption in Transit** | No | Recommended | Yes (TLS 1.2+) | Yes (TLS 1.2+, mandatory) |
| **Access Control** | None | All employees | Role-based, need-to-know | Role-based, need-to-know + MFA |

This is the part that actually saves time in practice — public data moves freely, while restricted data gets the full treatment: encryption, access logging, need-to-know only.

## Labeling

- Documents include a classification header/footer (e.g., "CONFIDENTIAL — Internal Use") on every page for Confidential and Restricted material
- Electronic files use classification-tagged naming conventions or metadata tags where supported
- Public and Internal materials aren't required to be labeled, though a general internal-use footer is fine

## Storage Isn't One-Size-Fits-All Either

| Classification | Approved Locations | Prohibited Locations |
|---|---|---|
| Public / Internal | Company intranet, approved shared drives | N/A |
| Confidential | Encrypted company file servers, approved cloud storage | Personal cloud storage, personal email, unencrypted USB drives |
| Restricted | Encrypted EHR/EMR systems, encrypted and access-logged storage with audit trail | Any unencrypted storage, personal devices, personal cloud accounts, unattended printouts |

## Transmission

- Confidential and Restricted data never goes out via unencrypted email — use the secure email gateway or an encrypted file-transfer solution
- PHI (Restricted) transmitted externally requires a signed Business Associate Agreement (BAA) with the receiving party
- Faxing Restricted data requires a pre-verified recipient number and a confidentiality cover sheet
- Public data can move through any standard channel without restriction

## Disposal Is Where Most Breaches Actually Happen

It's rarely the fancy hack that causes a data breach — it's the old hard drive that got thrown out without being wiped, or the box of paper records that went to regular recycling instead of a shredder.

- Paper records containing Confidential or Restricted data: cross-cut shredded or placed in locked shredding bins for certified destruction
- Electronic media: sanitized per NIST SP 800-88 (clear, purge, or destroy as appropriate) before reuse or disposal
- Disposal of Restricted data (PHI) is logged — date, method, responsible party — to support HIPAA audit requirements

## Access Isn't "Set It and Forget It"

- Access to Confidential and Restricted data is granted strictly on a need-to-know / role-based basis, approved by the data owner
- Access to Restricted data (PHI) requires manager approval, completion of HIPAA privacy training, and is logged in an access audit trail
- Access reviews happen quarterly for Restricted data, semi-annually for Confidential data, with immediate revocation on role change or termination

## The One-Page Version (For Everyone Who Won't Read the Full Policy)

### Quick Reference Guide

| Level | Ask Yourself | What To Do |
|---|---|---|
| **PUBLIC** | Is this already meant for anyone to see? | Share freely; no special handling needed |
| **INTERNAL** | Is this for staff only, but not sensitive? | Keep on internal systems; don't post publicly |
| **CONFIDENTIAL** | Could this harm a person or the company if leaked? | Encrypt, share only need-to-know, use secure channels |
| **RESTRICTED** | Is this PHI, credentials, or something severe if exposed? | Encrypt always, MFA required, log every access, never store on personal devices |

When in doubt, treat it as Confidential and ask your manager or Privacy Officer.

**The real point:** classification isn't bureaucracy for its own sake. It's what lets an organization protect what actually matters without grinding everything else to a halt.
